eVBi1vmZUrYY2SsvAO1Va3IgmbVnfm8NKDfuLO3UF1gZ3UV5QUrJpOLqZtSVPzFCqxHMEeGgIFwv154SogoZHu0vWhueLcIUPV41Nwvv13-PCeMdJc2RPwHevUwhERAIbUKyNKeXHI8GF7SED_d2DA4DXqS7yYVF_bmWE07k-X4xo3IQjjVhOQtgXj6ZuHw41G8bmcRBoR2ohpcxKkeW5BguMVT6Nw5b6PT4voELTQfKw4Fgzl_9MC268s1jHV-gBkhK39MvYdNloNJZVk-ld0Y63ek20_p_jOTywp466JH28QFcLYa42KR0pMAn-ibCOmlznaycvg0CSwjs2-Hi_KqbxFuLR3OMBj2lNg==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Explaining tool integration scope**\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfect use case. If it’s recurrent, a first-class tool is the right move.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Language:** usually **TypeScript/Node.js** (best fit with OpenClaw ecosystem), but any language works if exposed as a callable service/protocol.\n- **Where to put it:** either\n  1) inside your OpenClaw deployment codebase as a native tool module, or  \n  2) as an external tool server (cleaner separation, easier maintenance).\n- **How to call it:** once registered, the agent calls it by **tool name** with a validated input schema.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended implementation path (practical)\n\n### 1) Define the tool contract first\nDecide:\n- `name` (e.g. `crm_lookup`)\n- `description` (when to use it)\n- `input schema` (fields + types)\n- `output schema` (stable JSON shape)\n- error model (`code`, `message`, retryable/non-retryable)\n\nThis matters more than code language.\n\n---\n\n### 2) Implement handler (TypeScript recommended)\nYour handler should:\n- validate input\n- call endpoint (timeout + retry + backoff)\n- map raw response to stable output\n- sanitize secrets/errors before returning\n\nTypical stack:\n- `zod` (schema validation)\n- `fetch/axios` (HTTP)\n- structured logs\n\n---\n\n### 3) Register tool in OpenClaw runtime\nYou expose it in the tool registry so the model can see:\n- tool name\n- description\n- JSON schema\n- handler reference\n\nThen restart/reload the service so the tool appears in available tools.\n\n---\n\n### 4) Grant access intentionally\nScope it:\n- which agents/sessions can use it\n- env vars for API keys (never hardcode)\n- rate limits + audit logging\n\n---\n\n### 5) Test with real prompts\nTest cases:\n- happy path\n- invalid input\n- endpoint timeout\n- 4xx/5xx behavior\n- idempotency (if write operations)\n\n---\n\n## Folder suggestion (clean structure)\n\nIf you maintain OpenClaw extension code locally, use something like:\n\n- `tools/<tool-name>/schema.ts`\n- `tools/<tool-name>/handler.ts`\n- `tools/<tool-name>/README.md`\n- `tools/<tool-name>/fixtures/*.json`\n- `tools/index.ts` (registration)\n\n---\n\n## How the agent calls it (conceptually)\n\nOnce registered, the model does:\n- choose tool by description\n- send JSON args matching schema\n- receive JSON result\n- continue response using result\n\nYou don’t manually “invoke CLI” during normal chat — the runtime invokes it automatically when selected.\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can draft a **concrete starter template** for a `POST /endpoint` tool (with auth header, retries, timeout, schema, and registration stub) in TypeScript.","textSignature":"msg_040a9a3297cf14d40169aac7ad220c81919d5d321935cf38ef"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.3-codex","usage":{"input":494,"output":775,"cacheRead":7808,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":9077,"cost":{"input":0.0008645,"output":0.01085,"cacheRead":0.0013664,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.013080900000000001}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772799904749}}
